{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527192"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.33,0.03,0.01,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56309"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"3018"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17400"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56309"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her partner due to concerns about anxiety following a recent panic attack. She reports feeling constantly worried about various aspects of her life, including her job performance, finances, and health and feels she cannot control this, to the degree it is now affecting her sleep. She finds it difficult to make decisions in her life without extensive reassurance from others, particularly her parents and partner. She has difficulty initiating projects or doing things on her own due to a lack of self-confidence. These symptoms have been present for several years and are affecting her daily functioning. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears restless and tired with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obsessive-compulsive disorder","Dependent personality disorder","Panic disorder","Social anxiety disorder","Generalised anxiety disorder"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder (GAD)\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient exhibits key features of this disorder, including excessive and persistent worry about various aspects of life (job performance, finances, health) that is difficult to control and psychomotor agitation. Her symptoms have been present for several years, affecting her daily functioning, which meets the duration criterion for GAD (at least six months). It is important to note that panic attacks can occur in the context of GAD during times of severe stress or anxiety and does not equate to a diagnosis of panic disorder, which requires recurrent, unexpected panic attacks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPanic disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves recurrent, unexpected panic attacks followed by persistent concern about having additional attacks. The patient does not report experiencing sudden episodes of intense fear or panic, and she specifically denies having panic attacks, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDependent personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves an excessive need to be taken care of, leading to submissive and clinging behavior. While the patient does seek reassurance from others, she does not meet the full criteria for dependent personality disorder. Her primary issue appears to be persistent worry rather than a pervasive pattern of dependent behavior across various contexts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESocial anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by intense fear or anxiety about social situations where an individual may be exposed to possible scrutiny by others. While the patient appears anxious, her main concern is not about social scrutiny but rather about various life circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObsessive-compulsive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves recurrent, intrusive thoughts (obsessions) and repetitive behaviors or mental acts (compulsions). While the patient\u0027s need for reassurance might seem compulsive, she does not describe specific obsessions or compulsions characteristic of OCD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that anxiety disorders can have overlapping symptoms, and a thorough clinical assessment is necessary to rule out other potential diagnoses or comorbidities. Treatment for GAD typically involves a combination of psychotherapy (particularly cognitive-behavioral therapy) and sometimes medication, such as selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Generalised anxiety disorder (GAD) is characterised by excessive and persistent worry about various aspects of life that is difficult to control.","Generalised anxiety disorder often involves physical symptoms such as restlessness, fatigue, difficulty concentrating, irritability, muscle tension, and sleep disturbance.","Individuals with generalised anxiety disorder may seek frequent reassurance from others due to their persistent worry and lack of confidence in decision-making."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association DS, American Psychiatric Association DS. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. Washington, DC: American psychiatric association; 2013 May 22.","Van Ameringen M, Simpson W, Patterson B, Mancini C. Panic attacks in generalized anxiety disorder. J Nerv Ment Dis. 2013 Jan;201(1):52-5. doi: 10.1097/NMD.0b013e31827ab1f6. PMID: 23274296."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T23:28:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T23:29:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6874"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56309"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posit